tool.name: FindLocalPeaks

param.name: Input_Area
param.dialogReference: Polygon area of interest in which the local peaks are found.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Number_Of_Peaks
param.dialogReference: The number of peaks to find within the Area of Interest. The number of peaks returned may be less than the input value depending on the number of peaks in the area. You must enter a whole number.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Input_Surface
param.dialogReference: You must select an elevation raster layer. To run the model with a Mosaic Data Set, the user will need to browse to it using the folder icon. The tool will not show Mosaic Data Sets in the drop down box.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Output_Peak_Features
param.dialogReference: Output point feature class containing the local peaks returned by the tool.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

tool.summary: Finds the highest local maximums within the defined area. Peaks are found by inverting the surface and then finding the sinks in the surface. These points are then used to extract elevation values from the original surface, sorted based on elevation.
tool.usage:
• Find Local Peaks uses the Input Area as a processing boundary. Points are returned only inside of this area.

  • The number of highest point features returned may be less than the desired number. If you try 1,000 for a very flat region, you may only get a few points in return.

  • The elevation is used to rank points, but the number returned is based on the sorted order of elevation. If you choose the highest 10 points and points 10, 11 and 12 have the same elevation, the tool excludes the latter two.

  • Find Local Peaks finds local maximums in an area. Therefore it can determine a highest point on a small hill in the middle of a valley surrounded by high mountains.

  • The Elevation field stores the elevation of the output points.

  • Units are the units of the elevation surface.
